    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Balt.</placeName>
                <date>5. May 1830</date>
            </p>
            <p>My dear <addressee>Isaac</addressee>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)"><persName>Abbot</persName> forwarded me the enclosed check for
                2:50<lb/> which I must trouble you to collect and send it to me when you have
                an<lb/> opportunity. Your last letter was recd. and I hope I may be mistaken<lb/> in
                what I gatherd. from your letters—but <persName>Isaac</persName> I still discover
                from your<lb/> remarks that you will not permit any one to encroach upon <hi
                    rend="underline">your opening</hi><lb/> and as we all do enjoy opinions peculiar
                to each other, you must<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline"><sic>sumbit</sic></hi> to many with whom you associate, be them
                right or wrong if<lb/> you wish to go smoothly through this world. Hear what
                they<lb/> have all to say, but to dispute against the prejudices of
                <add>?</add><lb/> is vanity—success cannot attend it. Malice may persue.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I see too by the paper's a piece signed a “Native of
                    <placeName>Germany</placeName>”<lb/> the signature is familiar to me, but the
                substance of the piece is of<lb/> no importance to call you forth. do let me beg of
                you to keep<lb/> yourself more retired. Confound that catching propensity of
                yours<lb/> to be auspicious<add>?</add> before the public. I cannot see what is
                the<lb/> object. you hold a situation which if properly conducted, will<lb/> bring
                you before the community with more solid affections than<lb/> newspaper
                    <sic>scribling</sic>. I must object to you when I see you thus<lb/> pushing
                yourself before the public. I know it is pleasing to some<lb/> of your warmest
                friends, but now you have <del>
                    <add>?</add>
                </del> more than myself and I assure</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>you, you will live to regret it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Uncle Rehine</persName> has closed his shop on the last of
                    <date>April</date>, he<lb/> will wind up his business, and reside here by the
                next fall.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">We have heard of the success of <persName>Mrs. Saml.
                    Etting</persName>. You are <sic>choused</sic><lb/> of your fee for the want of a
                little s<add>?</add>, bad business <persName>Isaac</persName>, tho you must hope for
                better.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I cannot write long letters nowadays.<lb/> Remember me to all the
                good folks.</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">Truly yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <hi rend="underline">
                    <persName role="author">D Judah</persName>
                </hi>
            </p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <addressee>Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
